What is composed in Custom Events in LWC?
Companies that asked this: Deloitte, KPMG, Salesforce, TCS, Accenture, Infosys, Cognizant

Answer:
The composed property in custom events determines whether an event can cross Shadow DOM boundaries. In LWC, components are encapsulated within their own Shadow DOMs, so by default, events do not propagate beyond a component’s boundary.

Key Points:

composed: false (default) - Event stays within the same Shadow DOM tree

composed: true - Event can cross Shadow DOM boundaries

Essential for complex component hierarchies where components aren't direct parent-child

Works with bubbles: true for cross-component communication


Example

I’ll demonstrate how a custom event can travel from:

Child → Parent → Grandparent

Component Hierarchy
grandparent component

└── parent component

    └── child  component(event source)



Event Flow

A CustomEvent('notify') is dispatched in childComponent.

Because the event uses { bubbles: true, composed: true }, it:

Bubbles up to parentComponent

Crosses the Shadow DOM boundary

Reaches grandparentComponent

childComponent.js

import { LightningElement } from 'lwc';
 
export default class ChildComponent extends LightningElement {
    handleClick() {
        this.dispatchEvent(
            new CustomEvent('notify', {
                bubbles: true,
                composed: true,
                detail: { message: 'Hello from Child!' }
            })
        );
    }
}
childComponent.html

<template>
    <button onclick={handleClick}>Notify Grandparent</button>
</template>
parentComponent.html

<template>
    <div style="border: 2px solid blue; padding: 10px;">
        <p>Parent Component</p>
        <c-child-component></c-child-component>
    </div>
</template>
parentComponent.js

import { LightningElement } from 'lwc';
 
export default class ParentComponent extends LightningElement {}
grandparentComponent.html

<template>
    <div style="border: 2px solid red; padding: 10px;">
        <p>Grandparent Component</p>
        <c-parent-component onnotify={handleNotify}></c-parent-component>
    </div>
</template>
grandparentComponent.js

import { LightningElement } from 'lwc';
 
export default class GrandparentComponent extends LightningElement {
 
    // This will work because of composed: true
        this.addEventListener('notify', (event) => {
            console.log('Grandparent caught bubbling event:', event.detail.message);
            // Event continues bubbling (though it's already at the top)
        });
 
     // Template event handler (also works)
    handleNotify(event) {
        const msg = event.detail.message;
        alert('Grandparent received: ' + msg);
    }
}
